Part I - (Ford GoBike System Data)¶

by Oluwatofunmi Adedoyin)¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area. Some of the variables in the data set include the following

  1. duration_sec: The duration of each ride in seconds
  2. start_time: The start time for each ride
  3. end_time: The end time for each ride
  4. start_station_id: The duration of each ride in seconds
  5. end_station_name: The name of the end station
  6. user_type: The type of user, i.e. Subscriber or Customer
  7. member_birth_year: The year of birth of the Member
  8. member_gender The gender of the Member
  9. bike_share_for_all_trip: Rider preferences for all trips

Preliminary Wrangling Description¶

The cells above were used to understand the data set including preliminary wrangling.

The info, describe, shape, and dtype methods were used amongst others to understand the data set

All rows with missing data were dropped. Columns that will not be utilised in this analysis were also dropped. These were dropped to improve the quality and conciseness of the data.

The data type for member_birth_year was not ideal. This was converted to int data type

The cleaned data set was saved as df_cleaned. This is the data set with which Exploratory and Explanatory Visualisations will be generated.

The data type for the start station Id and end station Id were converted from float to string

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contains 174,952 rows and 12 columns.

Most of the variables in this dataset are categorical

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interest is the average duration per trip, including how gender, age and user preferences affect the duration of a trip

  1. Average duration for trips
  2. Gender demography for trips
  3. Age demography of trips
  4. User preferences such as subscription and bike share for all rides

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The features in the dataset that will help in the investigation include the following:

  1. duration_sec: This is the dependent value for this investigaiton.
  2. gender: The gender distribution in the dataset and its impact on the analysis
  3. user_type: The distribution of the category of the user in the dataset and its impact on the analysis
  4. bike_id: The distribution of individual bikes in the dataset and its impact on the analysis
  5. age: The age distribution in the dataset and its impact on the analysis!

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, we shall investigate distributions of individual variables.

Duration: Is the distribution skewed or symmetric? Is it Unimodal or Bimodal¶

In [624]:
# Defining a function for plot administration
def plot_names(title,xax,yax):
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xax)
    plt.ylabel(yax)
    ax.set(xlabel = xax, ylabel = yax)
In [752]:
plot_names('Fig 1: Histogram of Ride Duration','Duration(s)','Count')
bins = 10 ** np.arange(1,5+0.1,0.1)
ticks = [30,100,300,1000,3000,10000,30000]
labels = ['{}'.format(x) for x in ticks]
plt.hist(data = df_cleaned, x = 'duration_sec', bins=bins)
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xlim((30,13000))
plt.xticks(ticks,labels);

The distribution of the duration (s) is unimodal and right skewed

The distribution also indicates the presence of outliers in the data

Transformation was performed on the x axis (duration). This became necessary due to the large range of the duration values

Conclusions¶

The following inferences can be drawn from the analysis above

  1. There are significantly more male than any other gender type in the data set
  2. There are significantly more Subscribers than regular customers in the data set
  3. Men tend to use less time per trip on average compared to women and others
  4. People generally prefer not to share bikes for all trips.
  5. Males generally seem to be the highest contributors to station traffic relative to other gender types
  6. Top 12 stations have been identified with significant amount of rider traffic. This is useful information for ads, surverys or any other activity that would require engagement with riders 7.There is no significant relationship between the age of the rider and the duration of the trip
